WEST NILE VIRUS (45): EUROPE (GERMANY) HORSE, OIE
*************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Fri 18 Oct 2019
Source: Vetion (Germany) [in German, machine trans., edited]
https://www.vetion.de/aktuell/detailNews/32408/Thueringen-meldet-ersten-Fall-von-WNV-bei-einem-Pferd-18-10-2019/


In Thuringia, the West Nile virus (WNV) has been detected for the 1st time in a horse. The affected animal comes from the Unstrut-Hainich-Kreis near Bad Langensalza.

As reported by the State Veterinary Chamber of Thuringia, the diseased horse, which has demonstrably not been in WNV risk areas, showed neurological symptoms.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The above 1st horse case in Thuringia has been reported by the German authorities to the OIE in an immediate notification dated 16 Oct 2019; see with map at https://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapEventSummary&reportid=32128.

Another new WNF case in a horse has been reported to the OIE on Fri 18 Oct 2019, in follow-up report no. 6 of an event that started in Germany's eastern state Saxony on 13 Aug 2019. The report addresses a single case in a holding with 4 horses; the report, including a map showing the location of the case, is available at https://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapEventSummary&reportid=32164. Both cases have been diagnosed by antibody detection ELISA.

West Nile fever in animals has been reported during 2019 (since July) in 6 east German states ("Lander"); a total of 47 outbreaks have been registered as of 18 Oct 2019, affecting horses and several wild bird species, mainly captive birds. The locations of Germany's 2019 reported outbreaks in animals can be seen in OIE's global interactive map at https://tinyurl.com/y62uutaq (click on the German cluster, zoom in to the required resolution).

The Saxony event (18 outbreaks, of which 7 involve horses, the others in wild/captive birds) with links to all reports and an interactive map is available at https://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review/viewsummary?fupser=&dothis=&reportid=31473.

Total outbreaks = 18 (submitted)
